onsciousness. Examined from a variety of perspectives, from sociological to historical, their stories form a rich ethnography. While it is still too soon to tell whether stable, long-term democracy will prevail in Guatemala, the successes of these fascinating individuals provide a unique understanding of revolutionary resistance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aDisappeared personszGuatemala. 0aDisappeared persons' familiesxPolitical activityzGuatemala. 0aDisappeared persons' familieszGuatemala. 0aHuman rights movementszGuatemala. 0aState-sponsored terrorismzGuatemala. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aJesilow, Paul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71676640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292794733423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292794733/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK